<div id="review_2121156645" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2121156645" />
    <a title="Rebbie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6582211-rebbie"><img alt="Rebbie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1430858965p2/6582211.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2121156645?book_show_action=true">Sep 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rebbie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rebbie" href="/user/show/6582211-rebbie">Rebbie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6582211-rebbie?shelf=2017">2017</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2121156645" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11426354474775610430">What a lovely little book!<br/><br/>Simply put, this book is about two people of advancing age who are lonely, and make the decision to develop a bond and provide each other with comfort to get through the nights alone. Louis spends the night at Addie&apos;s home, and in doing so they grow to be close and dependent upon one another for emotional strength.<br/><br/>Both are widowed, and live in the same small town of Holt, CO. This is important because part of the book deals with nosy busybodies who can&apos;t mind their own </span>
  <span id="freeText11426354474775610430" style="display:none">What a lovely little book!<br /><br />Simply put, this book is about two people of advancing age who are lonely, and make the decision to develop a bond and provide each other with comfort to get through the nights alone. Louis spends the night at Addie's home, and in doing so they grow to be close and dependent upon one another for emotional strength.<br /><br />Both are widowed, and live in the same small town of Holt, CO. This is important because part of the book deals with nosy busybodies who can't mind their own beeswax. <br /><br />I found myself choking up during parts of this book (which is all too short, btw!), especially during the ending. I would have actually given this book 5 stars had it not been for the ending, but I understand that such is life and sometimes people make choices that I wouldn't make. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ I would have told her son to learn his place! Go pound sand, you adult brat! She supports him financially, yet he chases away one of the only good things she has going for herself. He has a lot of nerve, and my jaw dropped when I read how her son Gene was keeping Addie's grandson away from her just to chase away Louis. I thought it was very telling how Gene was mostly concerned about his inheritance and had zero problem with making his sweet little son cry with heartbreak over not being able to talk to his grandmother. I bet that jerk would have changed his tune real fast if she said "No grandson, no check. How do ya like them apples now, boy?" Ugh, I can't stand Gene!!!  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />The similarities to Cormac McCarthy's sparse writing style and (almost) run-on sentences were glaringly obvious here. I had no problem with it, because you know the old saying: imitation is the sincerest form of flattery. I think McCarthy would give his stamp of approval on this deeply moving story. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11426354474775610430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


